FT  02 MAR 93 / Letter: Why Mulroney's effect on society means he will not
be missed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr BRIAN MCNAMARA
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, While it may seem mean-spirited, I think that you will find that most
of your Irish readers would object to your characterisation of Brian
Mulroney ('Irish charm turns sour on Mulroney', February 25) as an 'Irish
charmer'.
Look at it this way: while you would perhaps be comfortable attributing a
stereotypically British characteristic - for instance, a 'stiff upper lip' -
to a politician of British origin, you would think again before headlining
Jesse Jackson's or Nelson Mandela's 'sense of rhythm'.
Innocent as it may seem, your Irish charmer label is in fact a stereotype,
with more negative images, such as the usual 'tendency towards exaggeration'
(which was included in the same article), never far away.
Brian McNamara,
