FT  01 MAR 93 / International Company News: Vard losses deepen to NKr213m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN FOSSLI
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
VARD, the Norwegian cruise and ferry group, reported an increase in net
losses in 1992 to NKr213.5m (Dollars 30.49m) from NKr180.9m a year earlier,
due mainly to a rise in foreign currency losses, high interest payments, and
a huge loss on the disposal of a cruise ship.
Vard forecast a weak first quarter for Kloster Cruise, its cruise business.
However, the group said it was continuing with efforts to improve its
capital structure through a disposal or equity partnership.
Last autumn, Vard declared its intention to find a partner to invest in the
cruise business.
Group revenue edged ahead to NKr5.47bn from NKr5.36bn while operating
expenses dipped to NKr4.67bn from NKr4.77bn. Net financial costs, comprising
mainly interest expenses to service debt, widened to NKr480.3m from
NKr399.81m, and foreign exchange losses shot up to NKr108.93m from NKr61.33m
in 1991. Group operating profit, however, advanced to NKr459.3m from
NKr274.4m
On the bright side, Vard's ferry business posted a record result last year.
